<h2 id="org88c4809">Resources</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org88c4809">
<p>
Below are (free!) resources that I've found useful in doing research. 
</p>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org8565d24" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org8565d24">Writing</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org8565d24">
<dl class="org-dl">
<dt><a href="https://jmlr.csail.mit.edu/reviewing-papers/knuth_mathematical_writing.pdf">Mathematical Writing</a> by Donald E. Knuth, Tracy Larrabee, and Paul M. Roberts</dt><dd>A quick read.</dd>
<dt><a href="https://georgegopen.com/articles">The Science of Scientific Writing</a> by George Gopen</dt><dd>A classic.</dd>
</dl>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org1753722" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org1753722">Computing</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org1753722">
<p>
Whichever language(s) you use, it helps to learn a little more than last time. 
</p>
<dl class="org-dl">
<dt><a href="https://adv-r.hadley.nz/">Advanced R</a> by Hadley Wickham</dt><dd>The "Foundations" and "Functional programming" sections seem to be universally helpful to any Statistics PhD student who mainly uses R.</dd>
</dl>
</div>
